1. Using a Dictionary with withColumns() (Recommended)
This is the cleanest and most efficient way to perform multiple transformations in a single call. 

```
from pyspark.sql.functions import col, when

# Define the columns you want to transform
score_cols = ["math_score", "science_score", "history_score"]

# Create a dictionary: { "new_col_name": logic }
status_map = {
    f"{c}_status": when(col(c) >= 60, "PASS").otherwise("FAIL") 
    for c in score_cols
}
```

# Apply all at once
df = df.withColumns(status_map)
Use code with caution.

2. Using a Loop with withColumn (Less Efficient)
While easy to read, this is slower because Spark must rebuild the DataFrame for every iteration. Use this only if you have very few columns. 
python
for c in score_cols:
    df = df.withColumn(f"{c}_status", when(col(c) >= 60, "PASS").otherwise("FAIL"))
Use code with caution.

3. Using List Comprehension with select()
This is the most "Spark-native" way to optimize performance, as it executes all changes in a single pass. 
python
# Keep original columns (*) and add the new calculated ones
new_cols = [
    when(col(c) >= 60, "PASS").otherwise("FAIL").alias(f"{c}_status") 
    for c in score_cols
]

df = df.select("*", *new_cols)
Use code with caution.

