Would you like to see how to calculate a "Total Score" that ignores null values instead of resulting in a null sum?

In PySpark, adding columns with standard arithmetic (e.g., col("A") + col("B")) will result in null if any of the values are null. 
To calculate a Total Score that treats nulls as 0 (effectively ignoring them), use one of the following 2025-standard methods:
Method 1: Using coalesce (Safest)
The coalesce function replaces nulls with a default value (like 0) during the addition without permanently changing your original data. 
python
from pyspark.sql.functions import col, coalesce, lit

score_cols = ["math_score", "science_score", "history_score"]

# Sum all columns, treating nulls as 0
df = df.withColumn("total_score", 
    sum(coalesce(col(c), lit(0)) for c in score_cols)
)
Use code with caution.

Method 2: High-Performance aggregate (Modern Spark)
For DataFrames with many columns, using Spark's built-in aggregate function on an array is more efficient than chaining many + operations. 
