(80, 70, 90)	80.0	80.0
(80, 70, null)	null	75.0 (Sum 150 / Count 2)
(80, null, null)	null	80.0 (Sum 80 / Count 1)
Would you like to see how to automatically "impute" or fill these null values with the column-wide average before you do any calculations?

In 2025, the most efficient and scalable way to impute nulls with column averages in PySpark is using the Imputer class from the Machine Learning library (pyspark.ml). This is preferred over manual agg and fillna loops because it is optimized for large datasets and handles multiple columns in a single transformation. 
Method 1: Using PySpark Imputer (Recommended)
This approach is highly performant and allows you to set a strategy like "mean", "median", or "mode". 
python
from pyspark.ml.feature import Imputer

# Define columns to impute
score_cols = ["math_score", "science_score", "history_score"]

# Configure the imputer
imputer = Imputer(
    inputCols=score_cols, 
    outputCols=score_cols, # Overwrites original columns
    strategy="mean"        # Options: "mean", "median", "mode"
)

# Fit and transform
df = imputer.fit(df).transform(df)
Use code with caution.

